<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-073-960  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 073 960.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Jan 1989 v18 n1 p117(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Inside Token Ring Version II, according to Big Blue. (IBMdevelopers describe 16M bps LAN)(part of a series)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Strole, Norm.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The second generation of IBM Token Ring Network products offers afourfold increase in transmission rate, from 4M bps to 16M bps, aswell as more efficient connectivity and additional levels of faulttolerance.andP;  The products are designed to offer a smooth migrationpath.andP;  Token Ring adapter boards operate at either data rate;software-controlled rate selection is made with adapter cards forPS-2 computers equipped with Micro Channel bus.andP;  LAN users withunshielded twisted pair wiring will need data-grade media foroffice-to-wiring closet connections and optical-fiber media formost wiring closet links.andP;  Network management and user applicationinterfaces remain unchanged.andP;  Netbios, TCP-IP and IBM SNAprotocols are supported.andP;  The 16M bps LAN enables interconnectionof slower-speed ring or bus networks via the faster backbone,permitting users to retain advantages of the slower-speed datarates.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM Token-Ring Network (Local area network) (productspecifications)IBM Token Ring Network 16-4 Adapter (Computer communicationsequipment) (product specifications).andO;Topic:     Token Ring NetworksSpecificationsEnhancementsTransmission Speed.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Typical LAN will be as backbone for slower-speed ring or busnetworks. (chart)Interconnection of multiple LANs over leased telephone lines.andO;(chart)Interface stacks. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>